-- usage --

encode() converts an integer to a short obfuscated string. decode() reverses
it. the encoding is deterministic and reversible - same input always produces
same output with the same alphabet.

```js
import id from '@prsm/ids'

id.encode(12389125)  // "7rYTs_"
id.decode("7rYTs_")  // 12389125
```

-- alphabet --

the alphabet determines the character set and output. changing it changes
all encodings. decode must use the same alphabet that was used to encode.

setAlphabet() for a specific alphabet, randomizeAlphabet() for a random one.

alphabet is module-level state, not per-instance. if you need multiple
alphabets simultaneously, you'd need multiple imports (not currently
supported - would need a factory function).

-- limits --

max encodable value is 2,147,483,647 (MAX_INT32). encode() throws if you
pass a larger number. this is inherent to the 32-bit modular arithmetic.
